**Project Overview**

The High Rollers is a strategic dice game that combines tactical decision-making with competitive gameplay. Building upon an existing working prototype developed in C++, the project will translate and enhance the core game mechanics using the Godot engine to create a polished, mobile–friendly experience. Players take turns rolling dice and strategically placing them in columns on their individual game boards, with the unique ability to destroy opponents’ dice when they successfully place two dice in the same column.

The game ends when all board spaces are filled, but victory is determined by the highest total score rather than completion speed. The scoring system adds significant depth through a multiplier mechanic where matching dice in the same column have their values multiplied by the number of matching dice, creating strategic decisions about whether to pursue high individual dice values or attempt to build matching combinations for bonus points.

The current prototype demonstrates complete functionality with console-based gameplay, including AI opponents with strategic decision-making capabilities, turn-based mechanics, and proper scoring calculations. The Godot implementation will enhance this foundation with 2D graphics.

**Target audience and motivation**

The High Rollers is designed for casual to intermediate board game enthusiasts who enjoy strategic gameplay with manageable complexity. The target audience include friends and family groups looking an engaging multiplayer experience that can be completed in 10-15 minutes per game. The game appeals to players who appreciate games like Yahtzee, King of Tokyo, or Splendor, where simple mechanics create meaningful strategic choices.

The dice rolling element provides enough randomness to keep games exciting and prevent any single strategy from dominating, while the column placement and destruction mechanics ensure that player decisions significantly impact the outcome. This balance makes the game accessible to newcomers while providing enough depth for repeat play and strategy development.

Our team is motivated by a shared interest in game design and the opportunity to create something genuinely entertaining. We are all avid board game players who have discussed game mechanics and design principles extensively, and this project provides our first hands-on opportunity to translate those discussions into a working digital game. The multiplayer aspect adds technical challenge while the strategic gameplay elements allow us explore game balance, difficulty and user experience design.

**Key features and discussion**

Core Gameplay mechanics

·  	Turn based dice rolling with strategic placement decisions  
·  	Individual player boards with multiple columns for dice placement  
·  	Destruction mechanic: placing two dice in a column allows destroying one opponent die in that same column  
·  	Game ends when all board spaces are filled, winner determined by the highest score  
·  	Scoring system combines raw dice values with multipliers for matching dice in columns

Multiplayer Experience

·  	Local Multiplayer support for 1-2 players  
·  	You play against either the computer, a friend on the same device or a friend online  
·  	Real-time score tracking

User Interface Design

·  	Clean, accessible interface suitable for players of ages  
·  	Individual player board sections with clearly defined columns  
·  	Turn indicator  
·  	Score display

Game Balance Features

·  	Random dice generation ensures fair gameplay across all players  
·  	Multiple strategic paths to victory

Technical Implementation

·  	Godot engine providing cross-platform compatibility and robust game development tools  
·  	Modular code architecture building upon the existing prototype’s structure  
·  	Enhanced AI system based on the current strategic decision-making algorithms

The existing prototype provides a solid foundation with complete game mechanics, including dice placement logic, destruct mechanics, scoring calculations, and AI opponent behavior. This reduces technical risk significantly as the core gameplay has been tested and proven functional.

 

 

**Preliminary interface sketches**

The existing C++ prototype provides a strong foundation for interface design, featuring a clear visual layout that effectively communicates game state and player information. The current console-based interface uses ASCII art to render dice faces with recognizable dot patterns, organized in a symmetrical layout with player boards positioned at top and bottom of the screen. Column organization is clearly marked, with real-time score displays for each column and total player scores prominently featured in the center.

The prototype demonstrates effective use of visual hierarchy, with the active player's rolled die displayed on their side of the board, column scores shown above and below each set of columns, and overall game scores centrally positioned for easy comparison. The interface successfully handles complex information display including individual column scoring, multiplier calculations for matching dice, and clear indication of game state progression**.**

The mobile version will build upon this proven layout structure. The main game screen will maintain the dual board approach but optimize spacing for mobile screens. Individual player boards will feature clearly defined column areas, and the central area will display the current player’s rolled die with clear visual indicators.

The Godot implementation will replace the ASCII art with polished 2D graphics while preserving the clear visual communication established in the prototype. The dice will be appropriately sized for mobile interaction while maintaining the organized column structure that makes the game rules immediately apparent to new players.

 

**Scaling plans**

Minimum Viable Product (initial version) The core version will focus on essential functionality to ensure a working game by the deadline. This includes single player mode against basic AI opponents, local multiplayer support for 1-2 players, mobile-friendly design, and clean 2D graphics that clearly communicate game state and available actions. 

Future Possible Features If development progress ahead of schedule, several enhancements could significantly expand the game’s appeal. Online multiplayer feature would allow players compete against friends remotely, expanding the potential player base beyond local sessions. Player profiles with progression systems could include difficulty unlocks that introduce new challenges or rule variations, visual unlocks such as custom dice designs or board themes, and a coin economy where players earn currency through wins that can spent on upgrades or new content.

Long-term Stretch Goals The lowest priority enhancement would be upgrading from 2D to 3D graphics, which would provide a more immersive visual experience but represents a significant technical challenge. This feature would only be considered if all other planned features are complete and substantial development time remains.

Development Strategy The team will prioritize the minimum viable product to ensure a polished, working game within the academic timeline. Additional features will be implemented in order of technical feasibility and player value, with online multiplayer and player progression taking priority over visual enhancements. This approach ensures that even if time constraints limit feature implementation, the final product will still provide an engaging and complete gaming experience.

**Risks and potential issues**

Technical Challenges  
A working prototype reduces most risks since the core logic, AI, and scoring are already implemented in C++. The main challenge is translating these mechanics into Godot’s GDScript and adapting the console interface for mobile touch controls. Limited Godot experience is mitigated by early prototyping and a clear understanding of the game structure.

Game Design Balance  
The prototype provides a solid baseline for balance, but adapting to touch controls requires rebalancing. The destruction mechanic and scoring multipliers will need playtesting to prevent dominant strategies.

Scope and Timeline Management  
With a defined prototype, scope is clearer, and focus is on adaptation rather than core design. Risks come from adding extra features, which will be avoided by sticking to a minimum viable product before considering enhancements.

Team Coordination  
Varying skill levels and academic schedules require careful coordination. Regular meetings, clear roles, and pair programming will support consistent progress and knowledge sharing.
